, England","Durham, Durham, England":"Durham, Durham, England","West Ayton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"West Ayton, Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1258–1314":"1258–1314","1235–1270":"1235–1270","1250–1298":"1250–1298","1250–Male":"1250–Deceased","1270–1320":"1270–1320","1276–1354":"1276–1354","1288–1350":"1288–1350","1200–1270":"1200–1270","1223–1315":"1223–1315","after 1270":"after 1270","before 3 September 1270":"before 3 September 1270","1350":"1350","1250":"1250","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","1315":"1315","1314":"1314","1259":"1259","1258":"1258","1235":"1235","1223":"1223","1288":"1288","1200":"1200","1354":"1354","1276":"1276","1298":"1298","1320":"1320","Sproatley, Yorkshire, England":"Sproatley, Yorkshire, England","West Ayton, Yorkshire, England":"West Ayton, Yorkshire, England","Goxhill, Lincolnshire, England":"Goxhill, Lincolnshire, England","Durham, Durham, England":"Durham, Durham, England","West Ayton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"West Ayton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Vere","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name, mostly from Vair in Ancenis, named with Gaulish <i>ver(n)-</i> ‘alder’. This was the probable home in the 11th century of the Breton lord Aubrey (Albericus) de Ver, who followed William the Conqueror to England and founded an influential family who held the earldom of Oxford until 1703. In a few cases the surname could be from other places in France, such as Ver in Manche and Calvados, which have the same etymology as Vair.","French (mainy Vendée; <b>Veré</b>): variant of <b>Vairé</b>, from Old French <i>vairie</i> ‘variegated, spotted’, applied as a nickname for someone who has freckles."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Isabel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."],"variants":[{"name":"Isabell","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isabelle","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , now in frequent use in the English-speaking world."]},{"name":"Isobella","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , which has been popular in England since the 18th century and has recently become the preferred form of the name."]},{"name":"Isobelle","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]},{"name":"Isobel","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Isabel ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":1,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":32,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Isabel de Vere was born in 1258, in Goxhill, Lincolnshire, England, her father, Simon de Vere, was 59 and her mother, Ada Bertram, was 35. She had at least 1 son and 2 daughters with William de Aton II. She died in 1314, in Sproatley, Yorkshire, England, at the age of 56."},"et":{"1258–1314":"1258–1314","1235–1270":"1235–1270","1250–1298":"1250–1298","1250–Male":"1250–Surnud","1270–1320":"1270–1320","1276–1354":"1276–1354","1288–1350":"1288–1350","1200–1270":"1200–1270","1223–1315":"1223–1315","after 1270":"pärast 1270","before 3 September 1270":"enne 3. septembrit 1270","1350":"1350","1250":"1250","12